Religion and politics is by definition an interdisciplinary domain of academic research. This course introduces the study of religion and politics from social scientific perspective in general, and from perspectives of comparative politics and international relations in particular. The course focuses on analytic tools, conceptualization of key terms, typologies, categories and theoretical approaches used by studies of religion and politics in political sociology, comparative politics and international relations.Objectives/eesmärkid:  - to analyze the relationship between religion, politics and society in the modern world - to introduce the concepts, theories and approaches used in academic analysis of religion and politics  - to compare the experiences of the Eastern and Western European countries are compared with the broader trends of religion and politics in non-Christian cultures/civilizations.Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  After completing this course, the student should:  1. Have an understanding of the key debates related to social scientific studies of religion and politics;  2. Know how to go about analyzing the themes, dimensions and aspects of religion and politics from social scientific perspective and be familiar with central concepts and theories as well as analytical approaches, typologies and categories used in the disciplines of comparative politics and international relations;  3. Have an understanding of key areas in which religion and national politics and-both religion and international relations interact;  4. Have an awareness of the ways how cultural, confessional, historic, economic and political contexts mould the patterns of religion and politics interaction;  5. Be able to identify the similarities and differences in ways how religious actors relate to political regimes and cultural communities, to political processes and public policies;  6. Have the ability to undertake independent social scientific research of religion and politics;   7. Be able to carry on an informed and informing conversation with others about the issues and problems related to religion and politics.
